voters<-read.csv("/Users/valentinafalanga/Desktop/DIDA 325 data & society/new-voter-registrations.csv")

#Introduction Voter registration patterns give us insight into trends within populations of the United States. Knowing how and when people are registering can give us an understanding of how we should allocate our resources, helping us to better serve the American people. The goal of this project is to better understand voter registration trends over time as well as between States. It is our hope that the results help others, such as campaigns promoting voter registration to the general public, understand where their efforts are most needed.

On a Statewide scale, we are interested in what states are performing the weakest in registering voters. Identifying these trends can help us focus our financial and organizing efforts into promoting voter registration within these states. Specifically, we can look for states that did not improve in average voter registration from 2016 to 2020.

On a broader, National scale, we are looking for months of the year in which voter registration performed best overall. What does national average voter registration trends look like over the 4 month period in both 2016 and 2020?

#Data Introduction and Cleaning

voters %>% 
  head(5)
#Jurisdiction: Name of the State
#Year: Year the data is from 
#Month: Month the data is from
#New.Registered.voters: Number of newly registered voters in that state that month

#Data types chr, int, chr, int

#renaming columns

voters_2 <-voters %>% 
  rename(NAME=Jurisdiction, registered_voters= New.registered.voters)

#Data Limitations

Some limitations of this data include that it is only from 2016 and 2020, skipping the non presidential election year of 2018 as well as only pull from a select few states, making it hard to generalize on a National scale. The timeframe being limited may limit our ability to see ongoing trends over that be more visible with a full year’s data.

#Most voters

voters_2 %>% 
  select (NAME,Month,Year,registered_voters) %>% 
  filter(registered_voters==max(registered_voters))
#The highest amount of new voter registration was February, 2020 in California with 238281 new registered voters

#Average voters

voters_2 %>% 
  summarize(Average_voters=mean(registered_voters))
#The overall average is 48223.46 new voters per month

#Only above average data

high_voters <- voters_2 %>%  
  filter(registered_voters >= 48223) 
 
high_voters %>% 
  count()

#new voter registration was higher than the overall average 36 months total

#Amount of times states went above average

high_voters %>% 
  group_by (NAME) %>% 
  count(NAME) %>% 
  arrange (desc(n))
#Texas went above the average 8 times, California and Florida 7,North Carolina 6, Illinois 4, Arizona 3 and Georgia 1.

#Top 3 states with highest voter registration averages

voters_2 %>% 
  group_by (NAME) %>% 
  summarize (mean = mean(registered_voters)) %>% 
  arrange (desc(mean)) %>% 
  head(3)
#California, Texas and Florida had the highest overall average voter registration.

#Visualizing Registered Voters By State

voters_2 %>% 
  group_by (NAME) %>% 
  summarize(mean_in_thousands=mean(registered_voters/1000))
ggplot(voters_2,aes(x=NAME,y=(registered_voters/1000),fill=registered_voters))+
  geom_bar(stat="Identity",position="dodge")+
  labs(x="State",y="Registered Voters (In Thousands)",title="Registered Voters By State")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1, vjust = 1),legend.position="none")


# Bigger states like California have the most newly registered voters by far, with Texas coming in second. Small states such as DC and Delaware have a fraction of the registered voters. As this data in not adjusted for population, this data may be more accurately represented by percent of the population that is registering, instead of raw gross.

#Visualizing Voter Registration in 2016 vs 2020

ggplot(voters_2,aes(x=Year,y=(registered_voters/1000), fill = Month))+
  geom_bar(stat="Identity")+
  scale_fill_manual(name="Month",values=c("black","darkblue", "blue", "lightblue","white"))+
  labs(x="Year",y="Registered Voters (in thousands)",title="Voter Registration in 2016 vs 2020")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 0, hjust = 0, vjust = 0),legend.position="none")


# There was clearly more overall voters registered in 2016 compared to 2020. Specifically, one month saw a dramatic decrease in voter registration from 2016 to 2020.

#Visualizing Voter Registration by Month

ggplot(voters_2,aes(x=Month,y=(registered_voters/1000), fill = Month))+
  geom_bar(stat="Identity")+
  scale_fill_manual(name="Month",values=c("black","darkblue", "blue", "lightblue","white"))+
  labs(x="Month",y="Registered Voters (in thousands)",title="Voter Registration by Month")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 0, hjust = 0, vjust = 0))

#Conclusion

From the analysis here, there is much that can be inferred about voter registration patterns across America. Despite the relatively restricted data, we can answer valuable questions. For example, while we asked what months of the year voter registration performed best overall, our analysis showed us very clearly that February performed the best, followed by March, January and April. May, on the other hand, performed abysmally compared to its counterparts, giving us valuable insight in voting registration trends. Those attempting to promote vote registration may want to focus their efforts on more popular months such as Jan-March and attempt to use the already existing momentum, or focus more on months such as May, when momentum has slowed. The Registered Voter by State visualization also gives these campaigns an idea of where to focus their efforts. States with higher populations such as Texas and California have big turnouts likely due to the sheer size of their population. Those wishing to promote voter registration should decide whether it would serve them best to focus on big or small states, whereas big states may result in bigger numbers, small states may be lacking personalized attention. Should we continue with this data, we would like to further explore state wide trends. Identifying states that have decreased in voter registration from 2016 to 2020 could be extremely valuable. In addition, expanding the data set would be ideal. More states, months and election years would help us better see trends when visualized. Finally, state population would extremely helpful in order to compare percent of population registering, rather than raw counts of people. This would better adjust for small vs big states in our analysis.

#Stakeholder Analysis

Our most prominent ethical concern in this situation is privacy and confidentiality breaches. While users may be consenting, their friends are not, meaning thousands of non-consenting people’s data are being sold and used against them through our product.

Most apparently, this situation is not abiding by the professional standard of upholding privacy and confidentiality. These severe breaches in non-users’ data is a serious issue and one we as a team must address immediately. Additionally, this raises concerns about whether we are contributing positively to society and working to reduce discrimination. The data sold is being used to in advertisements encouraging “unfavorable” populations not to vote, impeding on their constitutional right to vote. This raises serious question as to whether this product is negatively impacting the general population. Additionally, as isolated populationsare being targeted, one could argue we are actively supporting discrimination against these groups.

Despite this, I understand that we would like to continue working alongside this firm, as they are a loyal and profitable client. In order to serve the most people possible, while minimizing harm as much as possible, I propose instead of cutting off the firm, we impose new confidentiality regulations. We must ensure only data from conseting individuals can be collected. Any and all attempts at collecting data from friends of users but be harshly penalized and quickly removed. In this way, we can continue collaboration while minimizing harm to unwilling participants.
